    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, my realtor just mentioned i need to set up an escrow account for this house i'm buying in toronto. what actually is escrow and why can't i just pay the seller directly?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Escrow, in this context, is a trust account that holds funds until certain conditions are met, such as the sale of the property being completed. It's a way to ensure that the funds are released only when the agreed-upon terms are fulfilled. You can't pay the seller directly because escrow accounts are typically used to hold the funds for the following reasons: \n\n1. Protection of the buyer's funds: Escrow ensures that the seller doesn't receive the funds until the sale is complete, preventing any potential disputes or fraud.\n\n2. Compliance with regulations: In Ontario, where Toronto is located, the Residential Tenancies Act (RTA) and the Real Estate and Business Brokers Act (REBBA) require escrow accounts to be used in certain situations.\n\n3. Coordination of closing: Escrow helps facilitate the closing process by holding the funds until the sale is complete, and then releases them to the seller.\n\nIt's a standard practice in real estate transactions, and it's not just limited to Toronto; it's a common practice across Canada.",
