      "content": "okay that makes sense. so basically it's just like a neutral middleman holding the money so nobody gets ripped off? who actually manages the account, like is it the bank or the lawyer?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Think of the escrow account as a neutral middleman, holding the funds until the sale is complete. The account is typically managed by a third-party company, such as a title company or a law firm, that specializes in escrow services. These companies act as the escrow agent, ensuring that the funds are held securely and released only when the agreed-upon conditions are met.\n\nIn Toronto, the escrow agent is usually a lawyer or a law firm, as they are required by law to manage the escrow account. The lawyer will typically handle the day-to-day operations of the escrow account, including receiving and holding the funds, and releasing them to the seller when the sale is complete.\n\nIt's a bit like a bank vault, but instead of just holding cash, the escrow account holds the funds for the entire transaction, ensuring that everything runs smoothly and that the funds are released only when they should be.",
